summary: "Sansa has to speak gently with his tantrum throwing ass" I screamed. lol As much as I do enjoy the dymanic between the two, Jon...
question: "Sansa has to speak gently with his tantrum throwing ass" I screamed. lol As much as I do enjoy the dymanic between the two, Jon comes at Sansa with this strange energy. Like he gets defensive and pissed off if she disagrees or questions him. It will be interesting to see if he acts the same way if Arya or Bran disagree or question him. Will he accuse them of undermining him?
answer:
It’s like he jumps to the wrong conclusion in the worst way. She questions him along with the other lords and he starts berating only her like she did something horrible. This is after not giving her a heads up about any his plans. She tells him Cersei is a threat and he tells her she sounds like she admires Cersei, like what??? What part of ‘don’t ignore Cersei’ sounds like ‘Cersei’s the best’. It’s not like Sansa disagreed with all his plans, she didn’t mind training girls or having the Wildlings man the Wall. 

The only thing I liked is him choking Littlefinger and giving her the North (of course he would have. She’s the only Stark there).

summary: sansa’s relationship with power is so interesting because of course she’ll want some for herself since it acts as a form of...
body: sansa’s relationship with power is so interesting because of course she’ll want some for herself since it acts as a form of protection. the only difference between her and margaery was that margaery had a powerful family supporting her while sansa’s was being slaughtered. ignoring all evidence that contradicts this, sansa courting the northern and vale lords seems like a natural part of her character. it’s what she’s been trained to do since she was young, it adds a layer of safety around her. if people didn’t hate the idea of an ambitious sansa, they’ll accept that as another facet of her character.
